doc.ContractDescription: DNA REPAIR UNDER EXTREME CONDITIONS. SINCE DNA REPAIR IS AN ABSOLUTE REQUIREMENT FOR LIFE ON EARTH REPAIR ENZYMES MUST HAVE BEEN PART OF THE EARLY EVOLUTION OF LIFE AND THE BIOSPHERE. MODERN ORGANISMS HAVE SOPHISTICATED MULTI-ENZYME SYSTEMS THAT CAN REPAIR A WIDE VARIETY OF DNA LESIONS. HOWEVER, THEIR PROGENITORS MUST HAVE BEEN SIMPLER PROTEINS EVOLVED TO REPAIR A SINGLE KIND OF DAMAGE. BEFORE THE DEVELOPMENT OF OXYGENEVOLVING ORGANISMS THE OZONE LAYER THAT HAS PROTECTED LIFE FOR BILLIONS OF YEARS DID NOT YET EXIST AND DNA DAMAGE BY ULTRAVIOLET (UV) LIGHT ABSORPTION MUST HAVE BEEN EXTREME. THUS, ANY RECONSTRUCTIONS OF EARTH'S EARLY EVOLUTIONARY HISTORY MUST ACCOUNT FOR THE REPAIR OF UV LESIONS BY A SIMPLE REPAIR PROTEIN. SUCH PROTEINS WOULD HAVE DEVELOPED MECHANISMS TO DEAL WITH EXTREME TEMPERATURES. CURRENT THEORIES ABOUT EARLY LIFE ON EARTH SUGGEST THAT LIFE DEVELOPED AT TEMPERATURES NEAR THE BOILING POINT OF WATER. OTHERS BELIEVE THAT COLD ENVIRONMENTS MAY HAVE BEEN A DRIVING FORCE IN EVOLUTION. THESE HYPOTHESES BEAR DIRECTLY ON WHETHER LIFE COULD BE FOUND IN THE HARSH ENVIRONMENTS IN OUR OWN SOLAR SYSTEM. WHETHER HOT OR COLD, THEORIES ABOUT THE ORIGIN AND EVOLUTION OF LIFE MUST COMPLY WITH PHYSICAL LAW. ELECTRON TRANSFER (ET), FOR EXAMPLE, IS CENTRAL TO METABOLIC/SYNTHETIC PROCESSES IN THE CELL. ET IS EXTREMELY TEMPERATURESENSITIVE. FOR EXAMPLE, AN ACTIVATION BARRIER OF 10 KCAL/MOLE FOR THIS REACTION TRANSLATES TO A DIFFERENCE OF 300 IN KINETIC RATE IN GOING FROM 273 TO 373K. THUS, ET IN CELLS MUST HAVE ADAPTED TO THESE EXTREMES. A SECOND EXAMPLE IS THAT OF PROTEIN:MOLECULE INTERACTIONS. WE TAKE FOR GRANTED THAT SUBSTRATES OR COFACTORS CAN BIND STABLY TO THEIR TARGET PROTEINS AT AMBIENT TEMPERATURES, BUT WHAT HAPPENS WHEN THE SOLVENT IS NEAR THE FREEZING OR BOILING POINT? ONE OF THE MOST ANCIENT DNA REPAIR PROTEINS, DNA PHOTOLYASE (PL), IS AN IDEAL SYSTEM TO EXPLORE THESE ISSUES. PL UTILIZES PHOTOINDUCED ELECTRON TRANSFER (PET) TO REPAIR DNA THAT HAS BEEN DIMERIZED BY UV LIGHT (UV-DNA). PL REQUIRES A PHOTON OF BLUE LIGHT AS AN EXTERNAL ENERGY SOURCE. BECAUSE OF THE LIGHT-GATED NATURE OF THE REPAIR, SUBSTRATE BINDING, WHICH IS GOVERNED BY PROTEIN:DNA DYNAMICS, AND PET REPAIR OF THE UV-DNA ARE COMPLETELY DECOUPLED, AFFORDING A STRAIGHTFORWARD ANALYSIS OF THESE BASIC PROCESSES IN THE SAME SYSTEM. IN ADDITION, A STUDY OF THE DNA SUBSTRATE ELUCIDATES NUCLEIC ACID DYNAMICS AND UV-DNA YIELDS MODULATED BY ENVIRONMENTAL EXTREMES. WE PROPOSE A BROADLY INTERDISCIPLINARY APPROACH TO STUDY DNA REPAIR UNDER EXTREME CONDITIONS BY CHARACTERIZING AND COMPARING PHOTOLYASES CLONED FROM A HYPERTHERMOPHILE AND A PSYCHROPHILE. THESE PHOTOLYASES ARE ADAPTED TO TEMPERATURES THAT SPAN ~100 K. ENZYMATIC PET REPAIR OF UV-DNA WILL BE STUDIED BY VARYING TEMPERATURE/SOLVENT CONDITIONS. WE WILL DIRECTLY MEASURE THE ET AND REPAIR RATES USING ULTRAFAST LASER SPECTROSCOPY. A COMPARISON OF SUBSTRATE BINDING AND PRODUCT RELEASE AS A FUNCTION OF TEMPERATURE, PH, VISCOSITY, AND OTHER RELEVANT ENVIRONMENTAL PARAMETERS WILL ILLUMINATE THE SIMILARITIES AND DIFFERENCES THAT ARE REQUIRED TO MAINTAIN ROBUST DNA REPAIR CAPACITY IN HOSTILE HABITATS. OUR EXPERIMENTAL EFFORTS WILL BE COMPLEMENTED BY THEORETICAL CALCULATIONS OF DNA STRUCTURAL FLUCTUATIONS AND PROTEIN:SUBSTRATE UNDER A WIDE RANGE OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONDITIONS. IMPORTANTLY, WE WILL USE THESE SIMULATIONS AS INPUT TO COMPUTATION OF TEMPERATUREDEPENDENT ELECTRON TRANSFER KINETICS. THE MODELING, SIMULATIONS, AND KINETIC ANALYSIS WILL BE PERFORMED IN THE GROUP OF CO-I PROF. DAVID N. BERATAN AT DUKE UNIVERSITY. ADDITIONAL EXPERIMENTAL DATA CONCERNING SUBSTRATE BINDING THERMODYNAMICS AND COFACTOR REDOX POTENTIALS IN THESE EXTREMOPHILES WILL BE PROVIDED BY CO-I PROF. YVONNE GINDT AT LAFAYETTE COLLEGE (EASTON, PA). RESEARCH AT LAFAYETTE COLLEGE WILL INCLUDE THE EXTENSIVE INVOLVEMENT OF UNDERGRADUATES IN NASA-FUNDED RESEARCH. THE TEAM WILL BE HEADED BY PROF. R. doc.ContractDescription: THE PROPOSED PROGRAM INNOVATES NOVEL SENSING, PERCEPTUAL MODELS, AND ENERGY-EFFICIENT EXPLORATION STRATEGIES TO ENABLE MOBILE AUTONOMOUS SYSTEMS TO EXPLORE ICY MOONS AND IDENTIFY HIGH VALUE SCIENCE TARGETS. BEYOND TOPICAL RESEARCH, THE PROGRAM WILL INTEGRATE THE CAPABILITIES ON PHYSICAL ROBOTS AND DEMONSTRATE RESULTS IN ICY ANALOG FIELD ENVIRONMENTS. BESIDES ICY MOONS, THE RESEARCH ENABLES EXPLORATION OF PERMADARK CRATERS AND POLAR REGIONS WHERE DARKNESS IS JUXTAPOSED WITH GRAZING LIGHT AND TOPOGRAPHIC RELIEF. TERRESTRIAL APPLICATIONS INCLUDE ROBOTIC MODELING OF INFRASTRUCTURE LIKE BRIDGES AND ROBOTIC AVALANCHE RESCUE IN SNOW AND ICE. THE FIRST RESEARCH THRUST DEVELOPS ROBUST SENSING IN ICY MOON ENVIRONMENTS. THE OBJECTIVES OF THIS RESEARCH THRUST ARE TO (1) CREATE AN ACTIVE ILLUMINATION SENSOR THAT IS ROBUST TO AMBIENT ILLUMINATION AND STRAY SCATTERED LIGHT TRAVELING ALONG INDIRECT PATHS AND (2) DEVELOP STRATEGIES TO ADAPT THE ILLUMINATION, IMAGING, AND DEPTH RECOVERY ALGORITHM USED BY THE SENSOR ON THE BASIS OF TERRAIN TYPE, REQUIRED ACCURACY AND POINT CLOUD DENSITY, POWER BUDGETS, AND AVAILABLE ACQUISITION TIME. WE WILL ACHIEVE THESE OBJECTIVES USING A NOVEL ACTIVE ILLUMINATION SENSOR THAT CAN SELECTIVELY IMAGE CERTAIN TYPES OF LIGHT PATHS WHILE BLOCKING OTHERS WITH THE CAPABILITY TO SCAN OPTICALLY CHALLENGING MATERIALS SUCH AS ICE. THE PROPOSED SPECIALIZED SENSOR DEVELOPED THROUGH THIS RESEARCH WILL RUN A VARIETY OF DEPTH RECOVERY ALGORITHMS INCLUDING PASSIVE STEREO, ACTIVE SPACE-TIME STEREO, AND STRUCTURED LIGHT WITH THE FLEXIBILITY TO ADAPT TO EMERGENT POWER, TIME, AND ACCURACY TRADEOFFS. THE SECOND THRUST DEVELOPS DENSE PERCEPTION AND MODELING OF ICY SURFACES. THE TWO OBJECTIVES OF THIS RESEARCH THRUST ARE TO: (1) CHARACTERIZE THE PROBABILISTIC MODEL OF THE ACTIVE ILLUMINATION SENSOR IN REPRESENTATIVE ICY MOON ENVIRONMENTS CONTAINING ICE, ROCK, AND CLAY-LIKE MINERALS, AND (2) DEVELOP DENSE MAPPING METHODOLOGIES THAT ACHIEVE THE LEVEL OF REAL-TIME PERFORMANCE AND FIDELITY REQUIRED BY AUTONOMOUS SYSTEMS TO SAFELY EXPLORE ICY, CRAGGY ENVIRONMENTS AND ENABLE DETECTION OF HIGH VALUE SCIENCE TARGETS. TO ACHIEVE THESE OBJECTIVES, WE WILL DEVELOP A PROBABILISTIC SENSOR MODEL THAT WILL ACCURATELY DETERMINE THE DEPTH OF THE SENSOR MEASUREMENTS AND INNOVATE A PERCEPTUAL MODEL BASED ON SURFELS THAT WILL STORE INTENSITY, DEPTH, AND MATERIAL INFORMATION IN AN EFFICIENT DATA STRUCTURE. THE THIRD THRUST DEVELOPS EXPLORATION IN CRAGGY, ENERGY-CONSTRAINED ENVIRONMENTS. THE RESEARCH OBJECTIVES OF THIS THRUST ARE TO: (1) DEVELOP EXPLORATION STRATEGIES THAT ARE COGNIZANT OF PERCEPTUAL AND MOBILITY MODELS ALLOWING INCORPORATION OF SENSOR PERFORMANCE, MOBILITY CONSTRAINTS, AND ENERGY CONSUMPTION TOWARD MAXIMALLY INFORMATIVE ENERGY-EFFICIENT EXPLORATION, AND (2) DEVELOP REAL-TIME STRATEGIES TO ENABLE AUTONOMOUS NAVIGATION AND EXPLORATION IN CRAGGY, ICY ENVIRONMENTS VIA HIGH-RESOLUTION ENVIRONMENT MODELS DEVELOPED BY THE PROPOSED SENSING AND PERCEPTION METHODS. TO ACHIEVE THESE OBJECTIVES, WE WILL INNOVATE AN ENERGY-EFFICIENT MOTION PLANNING AND CONTROL FRAMEWORK BASED ON MOTION PRIMITIVES THAT MAXIMIZE THE INFORMATION GAIN PER UNIT ENERGY THE TRAJECTORIES WILL GENERALIZE ACROSS MULTIPLE MOBILITY PLATFORMS. TO ENABLE REAL-TIME EXPLORATION VIA HIGH-RESOLUTION ENVIRONMENT MODELS, WE WILL INNOVATE APPROXIMATE EXPLORATION OBJECTIVES THAT ARE AMENABLE TO PARALLELIZATION WHILE ENSURING ENVIRONMENT COVERAGE. INTEGRATIVE EXPERIMENTS WILL VALIDATE THE DEVELOPMENTS AT SITES IN PENNSYLVANIA THAT EXHIBIT SIMILAR CHARACTERISTICS AS THE ANTICIPATED CRAGGY, ICY ENVIRONMENTS. EACH FIELD EXPERIMENT WILL EMPHASIZE IN-SITU EVALUATION AND VALIDATION OF THE PROPOSED APPROACH
